From 909b90d6491100f9b0cfefb845c5d3ae2c5411da Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude Code <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sat, 25 Apr 2026 14:12:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] sdl3: opt into SDL_HINT_DOS_ALLOW_DIRECT_FRAMEBUFFER fast
 path on DOS
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Phase 7 framebuffer-paint fix (task #22). SDL3-DOS provides two
framebuffer-flush paths in vendor/SDL/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c:

  - Fast path (line 275 onward): system-RAM surface copied directly to
    VRAM via dosmemput (banked) or memcpy (LFB). Cursor compositing,
    palette sync, vsync, and page flipping are all skipped. Gated
    behind SDL_HINT_DOS_ALLOW_DIRECT_FRAMEBUFFER, default "0" (off).

  - Normal path (line 661 onward): full-featured blit through an LFB-
    backed surface with cursor + palette + vsync + page flipping.

Task #21's SDL/0002 diagnostic showed the normal path returns success
to every caller but paints nothing visible under DOSBox-X — every one
of 900+ DOSVESA_UpdateWindowFramebuffer calls hit the normal-path
branch tag, with SDL_RenderPresent reporting success 1000/1000 times,
yet the framebuffer stayed pure black. The bug is in the normal
path's banked-mode blit at line 806+.

Our use case doesn't need what the normal path adds:

  - Cursor compositing: game runs fullscreen, no SDL software cursor.
  - Palette sync between window and src surfaces: we use a single
    surface format end to end.
  - Vsync: Pentium-class hardware can't sustain >50 FPS reliably
    anyway; the original Cave Story spec is already tear-tolerant.
  - Page flipping: banked mode (which DOSBox-X's emulated 320x240
    INDEX8 hits) doesn't use page flipping in the normal path either.

So forcing the fast path is cheaper for us regardless of whether the
normal-path bug gets fixed upstream. The hint is set programmatically
via SDL_SetHintWithPriority(..., "1", SDL_HINT_OVERRIDE) immediately
before SDL_Init, identical shape to the existing patch 0029
(SDL_HINT_INVALID_PARAM_CHECKS) in this same #ifdef NXE_DOS block.

Why DOS needs this: only the DOS backend has this two-paths choice;
desktop builds use entirely different framebuffer pipelines. Guarded
by NXE_DOS to keep desktop behaviour unchanged.
---
 src/main.cpp | 26 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 26 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/main.cpp b/src/main.cpp
index 8c2070a..1bafafa 100644
--- a/src/main.cpp
+++ b/src/main.cpp
@@ -313,6 +313,32 @@ int main(int argc, char *argv[])
   // any env-read-timing concerns. Diagnostic for the Phase 7 black-screen /
   // 1647-drawSurface-invalid-error bug.
   SDL_SetHintWithPriority(SDL_HINT_INVALID_PARAM_CHECKS, "0", SDL_HINT_OVERRIDE);
+
+  // Opt into SDL3-DOS's direct-framebuffer fast path. SDL3-DOS has two flush
+  // paths (vendor/SDL/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c):
+  //   - "Fast path" (line ~275): system-RAM surface copied directly to VRAM
+  //     via dosmemput (banked) or memcpy (LFB). Gated behind this hint;
+  //     defaults to "0" (off).
+  //   - "Normal path" (line ~661): system-RAM surface blitted to an LFB-
+  //     backed surface, with cursor compositing, palette sync, vsync, and
+  //     page flipping.
+  //
+  // Task #21's SDL/0002 diagnostic showed the normal path returns success
+  // 1000/1000 calls under DOSBox-X but paints nothing visible — the bug is
+  // in the normal path's banked-mode blit (line 806+). Forcing the fast
+  // path bypasses that whole branch.
+  //
+  // Our use case doesn't need what the normal path adds:
+  //   - cursor compositing — game runs fullscreen, no SDL software cursor;
+  //   - palette sync between window and src surfaces — we use a single
+  //     surface format end to end;
+  //   - vsync — Pentium-class hardware can't sustain >50 FPS reliably anyway;
+  //   - page flipping — banked mode (which DOSBox-X's emulated 320x240 hits)
+  //     doesn't use page flipping in the normal path either.
+  //
+  // So forcing the fast path is cheaper for us regardless of whether the
+  // normal-path bug ever gets fixed.
+  SDL_SetHintWithPriority(SDL_HINT_DOS_ALLOW_DIRECT_FRAMEBUFFER, "1", SDL_HINT_OVERRIDE);
 #endif
 
   // SDL3: SDL_Init returns bool (true on success); old `< 0` check would always be false.
